        "answer": "d",
        "explanation": "A mirage is a type of atmospheric illusion in which the observer sees a non-existent water body, the inverted or enlarged image of a distant object, and many other distortions. When the distance between the object and the observer decreases, the illusion disappears and the observer is no longer able to see the distorted image. Mirage is a unique and astonishing effect of atmospheric refraction, commonly seen in hot deserts. During the daytime in a desert, when the layers of air near the ground become hot, they become rarer and less refractive than the cooler layers above. Thus, the light coming from a distant object gets progressively more deviated from the normal as it is refracted through the layers of air, and finally undergoes total internal reflection. As a result, the observer sees a virtual and inverted image of the object.",
