        "answer": "a",
        "explanation": "Relative humidity is the measure of the actual amount of water vapour present in air at a given temperature compared with the total amount of water vapour the air can hold at that temperature. The greater the amount of water vapour in air, the greater the relative humidity at a given temperature. Relative humidity changes considerably with change in temperature, even if the actual amount of water vapour in the air remains the same. When air temperature decreases, relative humidity increases, whereas when temperature increases, relative humidity decreases. Hence, Assertion (A) is true. The actual amount of water vapour per unit volume of air is called absolute humidity. Increase in temperature causes more evaporation, and the absolute amount of water vapour in air increases; that is, absolute humidity increases. Hence, Reason (R) is also true, but it does not correctly explain (A).",
