        "answer": "c",
        "explanation": "The temperature of the human body is ordinarily about 98.6 degrees Fahrenheit. No matter how much cold or heat there may be, the body temperature remains around 98.6°F. The constancy of human body temperature is due to the functioning of a biological temperature-regulating mechanism in the body. The hypothalamus of the brain acts as the controller of this process. One part of the hypothalamus works to maintain a higher temperature, while another part works to maintain a lower temperature. When the body temperature begins to rise, the control centre sends a message to the skin. As a result, sweating begins. Sweating reduces the body’s heat load and prevents the temperature from rising further. When the body temperature begins to fall below normal, the other control centre increases metabolism and muscular activity through its signals to produce energy, and thus the temperature remains stable. * The normal temperature of the human body is 98.6°F.",
